Indigenes of  Ijebu-Isiwo community in Ijebu-Ode local government area of Ogun State have embarked on communal effort to rehabilitate the eight-kilometer  potholed road leading  to the town. An initiative of  indigenes at home and in the Diaspora,  they have raised millions of naira to make the road motorable for the natives in preparation for the Ileya festival and the town’s Ojude Oba  ceremony that attracts all indigenes irrespective of religious belief. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network Championed by the Oluomo of Ijebu-Isiwo, Otunba Tunji  Ilelaboye,  work on the road had taken three intensive weeks  for completion. The traditional ruler of the town, the Lamodi of Ijebu-Isiwo, Oba Adedoyin Salisu, had commended  efforts of the people in rallying to the execution of the project. He commended the indigenes in the Diaspora for their financial contribution pointing out that it is heartwarming that in spite of their comfort zones abroad they remembered their roots. Successive governments of Ogun State had pledged to tar the road leading to the town, a border community with Epe in Lagos State, but had failed to redeem such pledges. A community  leader, Dr. Bisi Olawunmi, chairman of Aiyegbami-Isiwo Community Development Association,  expressed optimism  about government attention to the road  with the new administration  of  Govenor Dapo Abiodun  publicly  acknowledging the strategic importance of the Epe- Ijebu-Ode road as a major artery to boost development in that corridor of the state Meanwhile, the Ijebu-Isiwo Descendants Incorporation, Chicago, USA  is organising a one day medical outreach in the town on August  12, 2019 during which there will be health screening of indigenes.  According to the organisers, the event is slated for the second day after Ileya festival for maximum benefit for  the large number of  people who usually  come home for the festival.